Olivetti M20 FUZIX Port (Z8001)
================================

Hardware:
  CPU:       Zilog Z8001 @ 4 MHz (segmented mode)
  RAM:       512 KB (128 KB base + 3x128 KB expansion)
  ROM:       8 KB bootstrap EPROM
  Video:     MC6845 CRT controller, 512x256 pixels
  Serial:    Intel i8251A USART (DB-25)
  Keyboard:  Intel i8251A USART (via i8049 in keyboard)
  Timer:     Intel i8253-5 PIT (3 channels)
  PIC:       Intel i8259A (8 interrupt levels)
  Floppy:    FD1797 (160/320/640 KB)
  Hard Disk: WD1010 (optional, 11.25 MB)
  Parallel:  Intel i8255A PPI (Centronics)

Memory Layout:
  Segment B (0x8B): Kernel code (.text + .rodata)
  Segment 2 (0x82): Kernel data (.data + .bss), stacks, udata
    0x0000-0x003F   Reserved for BIOS workspace
    0x0100-0x017F   PSAP (interrupt/trap vectors)
    0x0200+         Kernel data, BSS, stacks
  Segment 3: Video RAM (16 KB)
  Segment 4: Boot ROM (8 KB)
  Segments 9-F: Available for user processes (448 KB)

Toolchain:
  Compiler:  z8k-coff-gcc 14.2.0 (https://github.com/tpaxia/gcc-z8k-14.2.0)
  Binutils:  binutils 2.46.0 (https://github.com/tpaxia/binutils-2.46.0)
             Must use the patched version — see "Toolchain Bugs" below.
  Flags:     -msegmented (z8001 segmented mode), no -mregparms

Calling Convention (z8k-coff-gcc, no -mregparms):
  Arguments:     Passed on the stack, right-to-left
  Return value:  r2 (16-bit), rr2 (32-bit)
  Caller-saved:  R0-R7
  Callee-saved:  R8-R13
  Stack pointer: RR14 (R14=segment, R15=offset)
  Segmented CALL pushes 4 bytes: PC offset at SP+0, PC segment at SP+2
  First argument starts at SP+4 on function entry

  IMPORTANT: This is NOT the register calling convention. All hand-written
  assembly must read arguments from the stack and return values in r2/rr2.

Emulation:
  MAME:  https://github.com/tpaxia/mame (M20 driver with CTS fix)
  Custom: https://github.com/tpaxia/z8000_emu

  MAME requires a one-line fix to src/mame/olivetti/m20.cpp:
    m_ttyi8251->write_cts(0);
  Added in the machine_reset function, next to the existing keyboard CTS
  line. Without this, the i8251A TTY USART never asserts TxRDY because
  CTS is not wired from the RS-232 slot to the USART.

  Run with:
    ./m20 -bios 2 -ramsize 512k -hard1 <hd_image> -rs232 terminal

Boot Process:
  1. BIOS loads bootloader SAV file from HD sector 33
  2. Bootloader reads kernel header from sector 64
  3. Loads .text to segment B, .data to segment 2 (per header)
  4. Jumps to entry point (segment B, offset 0)
  5. crt0.S: clears BSS, calls init_early, init_hardware, fuzix_main

HD Image Layout (256-byte sectors):
  Sector 0:    PCOS geometry record
  Sector 32:   VDB/extent record
  Sector 33:   Bootloader (SAV format)
  Sector 64:   Kernel load header (16 bytes)
  Sector 65+:  Kernel .text section
  Sector N:    Kernel .data section
  Sector M+:   FUZIX filesystem (optional)

  Built with: python3 mkm20hd.py bootloader.bin text.bin data.bin hd.img

Building:
  The kernel is not yet integrated into the main FUZIX build system.
  Manual build from Kernel/platform/platform-m20/:

  # Assemble platform files
  z8k-coff-gcc -msegmented -c m20.S -o m20.o
  z8k-coff-gcc -msegmented -c crt0.S -o crt0.o
  z8k-coff-gcc -msegmented -c tricks.S -o tricks.o

  # Compile C files (use the cross-compiler from gcc-z8k build)
  $XGCC -c -Os -msegmented ... devtty.c -o devtty.o
  $XGCC -c -Os -msegmented ... main.c -o main.o
  # etc.

  # Link with the PATCHED binutils linker
  z8k-coff-ld -m z8001 -o fuzix.bin -T fuzix.ld <objects...>

  # Extract sections and build HD image
  z8k-coff-objcopy -j .text -O binary fuzix.bin fuzix.text.bin
  z8k-coff-objcopy -j .data -O binary fuzix.bin fuzix.data.bin
  python3 mkm20hd.py bootloader.bin fuzix.text.bin fuzix.data.bin hd.img

Toolchain Bugs:
  1. Binutils R_IMM32 segmented relocation (CRITICAL)
     File: bfd/coff-z8k.c, extra_case(), R_IMM32 handler
     Bug:  The relocation transform extracts the segment number from bits
           23-16 of the VMA, but z8k-coff stores it in bits 31-24. Bits
           23-16 are always zero, so every segmented address gets segment 0.
     Fix:  Remove the transform — the VMA is already in Z8001 long-form
           segmented encoding (1SSSSSSS 00000000 OOOOOOOO OOOOOOOO).
           Just write the value directly with bfd_put_32().
     Test: See ~/Projects/binutils-bug/ for a minimal reproducer.
     Commit: https://github.com/tpaxia/binutils-2.46.0 (main branch)

  2. GCC z8k return value register (UNDER INVESTIGATION)
     The d_open() return value check appears to malfunction: tty_open
     returns 0 (success) but the caller sees non-zero. The generated
     code (test r2 / jr eq) looks correct. Root cause still unknown —
     may be a MAME Z8001 emulation issue or a subtle codegen problem.

i8251A USART Notes:
  The serial port USART must be explicitly initialized by the kernel.
  The BIOS init state may not survive the boot process. Init sequence:
    0x00 x3 (sync), 0x40 (reset), 0xCE (mode: 8N1, x16), 0x37 (command:
    RTS, DTR, error reset, RxEN, TxEN), then flush with a data read.

  TxRDY (status bit 0) is gated by CTS in hardware. Since MAME doesn't
  wire CTS, the kernel checks TxEMPTY (bit 2) instead, which is not
  gated by CTS. This applies to both _outchar in m20.S and tty_putc/
  tty_writeready in devtty.c.

  Baud rate: PIT counter 0, divisor 8, mode 3 → 9615 baud (x16 clock).

Current Status:
  - Kernel boots and prints the FUZIX version banner on serial port
  - Panics or crashes shortly after (investigating tty_open return and
    subsequent function calls)
  - No block device driver yet (floppy/HD via BIOS ROM calls planned)
  - No filesystem mount
  - No user-space execution
  - Context switching (tricks.S) untested
  - Interrupt handling (NVI timer, VI) untested
  - Signal delivery not implemented

Open Issues:
  - Investigate d_open/tty_open return value mismatch
  - Crash after FUZIX banner (jumps to segment 0)
  - pagemap_init uses incorrect 32-bit arithmetic for segmented addresses
  - BIOS disk driver needed for block device access
  - PSAP vector table not populated with handler addresses
  - Interrupts not enabled (PIC masked, PSAP not set up)
  - User-space memory management for segmented mode
  - Signal delivery mechanism
  - Proper kernel memory layout across segments
